Her eyes were either removed by the guards before the execution or by herself to avoid marrying a Pagan man. According to the latter legend, she gifted the eyes to him. The eyes were miraculously restored before Lucia''s body was prepared for burial. Palm represents martyrdom and victory over evil. Candle, lamp and similar attributes refer to St. Lucia carrying supplies for persecuted Christians in catacombs in Syracuse. In Scandinavia St. Lucia is allegorically symbolized as a lady in white dress with red sash (symbolizing blood) and a crown of candles (because here hands were full with supplies). Remaining symbols point to failed attempts by Roman guards to take Lucia away to the brothel by hitching her to a team of oxen, and to set Lucia on fire, before Lucia is killed by the sword.", "dagger, carrying eyes (often on a plate), flames, torch, candle or lamp, a palm, cord. Often hitched to oxen or before the judge.", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Lucy");
As one of the four eminent Latin doctors of the Church from early Middle Ages (the ""Fathers of the Church""), he is often portrayed anachronistically in the garb of a cardinal, although cardinals did not yet exist and the term was first used to refer to deacons of the regions of Rome only in the 6th century. Model of a church in his hands also serves the purpose of showing Jerome as a doctor of the Church. A lion points to a legend that Jerome had tamed a lion in the wilderness by healing its paw. The story likely stems from confusion between Jerome and Saint Gerasimus or simply from the tale of Androcles. Jerome spent many years in Syrian desert of Chalcis, which is why artists often depict him in ""wilderness"", but in Western European art it often takes form of a forest. Jerome is often depicted with symbols of the vanitas motif, the meaninglessness of earthly life, such as hourglasses, skulls, inscriptions ""Cogita Mori"" etc. Owl is used as a symbol of scholarship.", "Bible, skull, lion, model of a church, owl, writing materials, trumpet (of final judgement), red hat (galero) or garb of a cardinal. Often shown as an aged monk in desert, or translating the Bible.", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerome");
