Three stories are usually depicted in art. The most common story from the Golden Legend describes the saint helping a devout man who lost his money due to ""plotting and envy of Satan"" and could not afford dowry for his three daughters. Nicholas secretly threw a bag of gold throw a window opening for each of the three nights. This story eventually gave rise to traditional model of Santa Claus. The second story, also from Golden Legend, describes Nicholas reviving three innocent soldiers unjustly condemnded to death by the bribed governor Eustathius. Due to ambiguity in the word carnificina (execution-place or butcher shop) the story has many versions, with a butcher or an inn-keeper taking the place of the governor, young nobles or students taking place of the soldiers. In case of a butcher, the innocents were chopped and put in a pickling barrel, but St. Nicholas put pieces back together and revived them with a Sign of the Cross. This popular story is depicted in many mediums from tapestries to glass windows. Finally in a third story Nicholas saves the ship from a tempest. In some versions, he himself is a passenger for a trip to Holy Land, and in some the latter two stories blend into one. In Eastern Christianity, Nicholas is often shown wearing omophorion and holding Gospel with Theotokos and Jesus Christ at each shoulder.", "Bishop vestments, mitre or bareheaded, three gold balls", "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Nicholas");
